{"tool":"write_file","args":{"path":"docs/SUBSYSTEMS.md","content":"# SUBSYSTEMS: USB-C Power Breakout\n\nStage 2 (architecture). This document decomposes the board defined in\n`docs/SPEC.md` into subsystems, with the reasoning and key values for each.\nEvery value here is held against the budgets in SPEC.md §3. This is a\n**passive 5V pass-through sink**: there is no MCU, no connectivity, no\nregulation, and no USB-PD negotiation. The subsystems that a generic\n\"power, MCU, connectivity, UI\" template would expect but that are\ndeliberately absent are enumerated in §8 so their absence reads as\nintentional, not as an oversight.\n\n## 1. Block diagram (prose)\n\nPower flows in one direction, source → load:\n\n```\n   USB-C source (charger/host)\n            │  VBUS (5V nominal, ≤6V survive), GND\n            ▼\n  [1] USB-C receptacle (sink-wired)\n            │────────────► [2] CC1/CC2 each via Rd (5.1k) → GND\n            │                     (advertises \"sink attached\", turns VBUS on)\n            │\n            ├────────────► [4] TVS across VBUS/GND (ESD/surge clamp)\n            │\n            ▼\n  [3] Short-circuit protection (resettable current limiter, VBUS in-line)\n            │  VBUS_PROT (protected 5V)\n            ├────────────► [6] Power-good LED + series resistor → GND\n            │\n            ▼\n  [5] Output distribution\n            ├──► 2-pin 3.5mm screw terminal (VBUS_PROT, GND)\n            └──► 2x2 0.1\" pin header (VBUS_PROT, GND)\n\n  [7] Mechanical: 2x M3 through-hole, 24mm pitch (no net)\n```\n\nNet names used downstream: `VBUS` (raw from receptacle, pre-protection),\n`VBUS_PROT` (post-protection rail feeding LED + outputs), `GND`,\n`CC1`, `CC2`. D+/D- are intentionally unrouted (SPEC §6).\n\n## 2. [1] USB-C input (receptacle)\n\n- **Function:** Accept 5V VBUS/GND from a standard USB-C source, sink-wired\n  only. Mates with a user-supplied USB-C cable.\n- **Key values:** VBUS 5V nominal, must survive up to 6V (SPEC §3). Power\n  pins and the downstream copper are rated for 3A continuous (SPEC §3.1) —\n  a *rating*, not a negotiated current. Use all VBUS and GND power pins in\n  parallel on the receptacle to share the 3A.\n- **Reasoning:** A receptacle (not a plug) because the board is the sink and\n  the user brings a cable. Data pins (D+/D-, SBU) are left unconnected;\n  only VBUS, GND, CC1, CC2 are used. Part number and exact footprint\n  deferred to part-selection (must be hand-solderable per SPEC §4).\n\n## 3. [2] CC sink termination (Rd)\n\n- **Function:** Present a legal USB-C sink so a compliant source enables\n  VBUS. Each of CC1 and CC2 terminates to GND through its own pull-down\n  resistor Rd.\n- **Key values:** Rd = 5.1kΩ to GND on **each** CC pin, independently\n  (two resistors, one per CC pin — never share a single Rd, or orientation\n  detection breaks). 5.1kΩ is the USB Type-C spec value for a sink\n  presenting the default (Rp-independent) Rd termination. The value and\n  its rationale are the single detail most likely to be wrong and are\n  recorded in `docs/DECISIONS.md`.\n- **Reasoning:** No CC logic, no PD PHY, no e-marker. Two discrete 5.1k\n  resistors are the entire \"negotiation.\" This is why the board reads\n  only 5V default USB current and cannot request more (SPEC §3.1).\n- **Quiescent impact:** At 5V a 5.1k Rd only draws current when the source\n  drives Rp; steady-state CC draw is negligible against the <2mA budget.\n\n## 4. [3] Short-circuit protection\n\n- **Function:** Protect the output against a downstream short without\n  damaging the board, connector, or source (SPEC §2.5). In-line on VBUS\n  between the receptacle and the output distribution.\n- **Key values (ASSUMED, see SPEC §5):** resettable, auto-recovering\n  current limiter (eFuse/PTC-style), trip threshold 3.5–4A — above the 3A\n  continuous rating for headroom, below a level that would stress the\n  connector. Device quiescent/bias current must fit the ≤1mA \"everything\n  else\" slice of the 2mA budget (SPEC §3.2).\n- **Reasoning:** Auto-recovery avoids a dead board after a transient short\n  (better for a breadboard tool than a one-time fuse). Exact part, trip\n  point, and Iq recorded in `docs/DECISIONS.md` at part-selection and\n  checked against §3.2.\n\n## 5. [4] ESD / surge protection\n\n- **Function:** Clamp ESD/surge events at the user-facing connector.\n- **Key values (ASSUMED, see SPEC §5):** one low-capacitance TVS diode\n  across VBUS/GND at the receptacle. Working/standoff voltage above 6V\n  (survive limit) and below the clamp that would matter, so it never\n  conducts in normal 5V operation — zero contribution to quiescent draw.\n- **Reasoning:** The receptacle is a plausible ESD entry point; standard\n  practice for an exposed connector. Must be checked against the <$3 BOM\n  target at part-selection.\n\n## 6. [5] Output distribution\n\n- **Function:** Present protected 5V (`VBUS_PROT`) and GND to the user.\n- **Key values:** (a) 2-pin screw terminal, 3.5mm pitch, rated ≥3A; (b)\n  2x2 0.1\" (2.54mm) pin header, VBUS_PROT and GND. All output copper sized\n  for 3A continuous at 1oz (trace width set at layout stage).\n- **Reasoning:** Two output styles cover both permanent hookup (screw\n  terminal) and breadboard/jumper use (header). Both carry the same\n  post-protection rail.\n\n## 7. [6] Power-good LED / UI\n\n- **Function:** Visible indication that VBUS is present (SPEC §2.4). LED +\n  series resistor from `VBUS_PROT` to GND.\n- **Key values:** LED branch current ≤ 1mA (SPEC §3.2 allocation). At\n  ~5V rail with a typical ~2V LED Vf, series resistor ≈ 3.0–3.3kΩ gives\n  ~0.9–1.0mA — under the 1mA slice. Resistor and LED ≥0603 (SPEC §4).\n- **Reasoning:** The LED is the only always-on load, so it dominates the\n  quiescent budget; sizing it ≤1mA leaves ≥1mA for the protection device\n  and keeps total under the 2mA hard limit. Fed from VBUS_PROT so a short\n  that trips protection also extinguishes the LED (useful feedback).\n\n## 8. Absent subsystems (intentional)\n\nThese are deliberately **not** on the board. Recorded so a reviewer does\nnot read a missing block as an error.\n\n- **MCU / microcontroller — absent.** The board does nothing programmable;\n  CC termination is two passive resistors. No firmware, no strapping pins,\n  no debug header. Adding an MCU would blow the <$3 BOM and <2mA quiescent\n  budgets for zero functional gain.\n- **Connectivity (USB data, wireless, comms) — absent.** D+/D-/SBU are not\n  routed (SPEC §6). No radio, no antenna, no keepout concerns.\n- **Voltage regulation — absent.** Output is a straight 5V pass-through;\n  there is no DC-DC or LDO. The board never produces a rail other than the\n  input 5V (SPEC §6).\n- **USB-PD / BC1.2 / negotiation — absent.** No PD PHY, no CC logic. The\n  board presents Rd and takes default USB current only. \"3A\" is a\n  copper/connector/protection *rating*, never a negotiated or requested\n  current (SPEC §3.1). This must not be implied in schematic notes,\n  silkscreen, or BOM.\n\n## 9. Traceability\n\nDerived from `docs/SPEC.md`. Budgets enforced: 3A rating (§2,4,6), 5V/6V\n(§2,5), <2mA quiescent with LED ≤1mA (§4,7), ≤30x20mm and 24mm M3 pitch\n(§10 mechanical / layout stage), <$3 BOM (§4,5), 0603-minimum hand-solder\n(§6,7). ASSUMED items (protection method/trip, TVS, temp range) carry\nthrough from SPEC §5 and are revisited at part-selection.\n"}}
